        <img data-original="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/04/02/gettyimages-1208677867-e6749f892391c92ae2513a16ff6c4d69b57966fd-s1200.jpg" alt="" />
    </div>
</div>
<div class="enlarge_html">
    <div class="image_data">
        <p class="caption">Zoom is wildly popular, but it's now under scrutiny for security and privacy issues.</p>
        <span class="credit" aria-label="Image credit">
            
            Olivier Douliery/AFP via Getty Images
            
        </span>
    </div>
</div>
   </div>
   <p><strong>Updated at 11:22 a.m. ET</strong></p>   <p>Dennis Johnson fell victim last week to a new form of harassment known as "Zoombombing," in which intruders hijack video calls and post hate speech and offensive images such as pornography. It's a phenomenon so alarming that the FBI has issued a warning about using Zoom.</p>   <p>Like many people these days, Johnson is doing a lot of things over the Internet that he would normally do in person. Last week, he defended his doctoral dissertation in a Zoom videoconference.</p>   <p>He had a big audience — he estimated it was about 40 people, including "my closest friends, family and my classmates and my dissertation committee" at California State University, Long Beach, he said.</p>   <div id="res827088935" class="bucketwrap internallink insettwocolumn inset2col ">
            <div class="bucket img">
                  <a id="featuredStackSquareImage826968159" href="https://www.npr.org/2020/04/03/826968159/senator-zoom-deceived-users-over-its-security-claims"  data-metrics='{"category":"Story to Story","action":"Click Internal Link","label":"https:\/\/www.npr.org\/2020\/04\/03\/826968159\/senator-zoom-deceived-users-over-its-security-claims"}' ><img src="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/04/03/gettyimages-1208882806_sq-d937fab682338f192f64b5d01afbc4a2dafb95de-s100-c15.jpg" data-original="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/04/03/gettyimages-1208882806_sq-d937fab682338f192f64b5d01afbc4a2dafb95de-s100.jpg" class="img lazyOnLoad"  alt="Senator Asks FTC To Investigate Zoom's 'Deceptive' Security Claims" /></a>         <div class="bucketblock">
                        <h3 class="slug"><a href="https://www.npr.org/series/812054919/the-coronavirus-crisis">The Coronavirus Crisis </a></h3>
            <h3><a href="https://www.npr.org/2020/04/03/826968159/senator-zoom-deceived-users-over-its-security-claims"  data-metrics='{"category":"Story to Story","action":"Click Internal Link","label":"https:\/\/www.npr.org\/2020\/04\/03\/826968159\/senator-zoom-deceived-users-over-its-security-claims"}' >Senator: Zoom Deceived Users Over Its Security Claims</a></h3>
         </div>
         
<!-- END CLASS="BUCKETBLOCK" -->
      </div>
      
<!-- END CLASS="BUCKET IMG" -->
   </div>
   
<!-- END ID="RES827088935" CLASS="BUCKETWRAP INTERNALLINK INSETTWOCOLUMN INSET2COL " -->
   <p>Johnson is the first member of his family to graduate from college, let alone get a doctorate. He wanted to share the moment with them.</p>   <p>He said he was in the middle of presenting when someone started drawing male genitalia on the screen. At first, Johnson said, he was not sure what was happening.</p>   <p>"I'm like, 'Whoa!' And then I freeze, and everyone who's watching the screen freezes," he said.</p>   <p>It got worse. The attacker scrawled a racial slur that everyone on the Zoom call could see.</p>   <aside id="ad-backstage-wrap" aria-label="advertisement">
    

    <div id="ad-backstage-News_Technology" class="ad-backstage" data-ad-config='{"network":"\/6735\/","site":{"default":"n6735.NPR","mobile":"n6735.NPRMOBILE"},"zone":"News_Technology","targets":{"testserver":"false","isPodcastEpisode":"false","storyId":"826129520","program":"Morning_Edition","agg":["812054919","711349494","191676894","434975886","1095"]},"location":"backstage","deferred":false,"isBetweenContent":true,"isAggSponsorship":false,"borderClass":""}'></div>

</aside>   <div id="res826609765" class="bucketwrap internallink insettwocolumn inset2col ">
            <div class="bucket img">
                  <a id="featuredStackSquareImage826224938" href="https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/02/826224938/video-meeting-platform-zoom-addresses-criticisms-as-it-sees-explosive-growth-in"  data-metrics='{"category":"Story to Story","action":"Click Internal Link","label":"https:\/\/www.npr.org\/sections\/coronavirus-live-updates\/2020\/04\/02\/826224938\/video-meeting-platform-zoom-addresses-criticisms-as-it-sees-explosive-growth-in"}' ><img src="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/04/02/ap_20085547111460_sq-c88f556667ce3ad141940ede4cde5a2abb661ec6-s100-c15.jpg" data-original="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/04/02/ap_20085547111460_sq-c88f556667ce3ad141940ede4cde5a2abb661ec6-s100.jpg" class="img lazyOnLoad"  alt="Video Meeting Platform Zoom Addresses Criticisms As It Sees Explosive Growth In Users" /></a>         <div class="bucketblock">
                        <h3 class="slug"><a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/">Coronavirus Live Updates </a></h3>
            <h3><a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/02/826224938/video-meeting-platform-zoom-addresses-criticisms-as-it-sees-explosive-growth-in"  data-metrics='{"category":"Story to Story","action":"Click Internal Link","label":"https:\/\/www.npr.org\/sections\/coronavirus-live-updates\/2020\/04\/02\/826224938\/video-meeting-platform-zoom-addresses-criticisms-as-it-sees-explosive-growth-in"}' >Video Meeting Platform Zoom Addresses Criticisms As It Sees Explosive Growth In Users</a></h3>
         </div>
         
<!-- END CLASS="BUCKETBLOCK" -->
      </div>
      
<!-- END CLASS="BUCKET IMG" -->
   </div>
   
<!-- END ID="RES826609765" CLASS="BUCKETWRAP INTERNALLINK INSETTWOCOLUMN INSET2COL " -->
   <p>Johnson was horrified. The organizers blocked everyone's screen until they could remove the intruder from the meeting. But, Johnson said, they were not able to identify that person.</p>   <p>Although he was shaken, Johnson managed to finish his presentation. But what should have been a triumphant celebration was ruined.</p>   <p>"The moment they [told] me, 'Congratulations, Dr. Dennis Johnson,' and it's all over and I leave the Zoom meeting, everything sets in," he said. "I couldn't even, like, communicate. I had to just walk out [of] my house. ... I didn't want to talk or see anybody."</p>   <div id="res826164631" class="bucketwrap internallink insettwocolumn inset2col ">
            <div class="bucket img">
                  <a id="featuredStackSquareImage817154787" href="https://www.npr.org/2020/03/17/817154787/internet-traffic-surges-as-companies-and-schools-send-people-home"  data-metrics='{"category":"Story to Story","action":"Click Internal Link","label":"https:\/\/www.npr.org\/2020\/03\/17\/817154787\/internet-traffic-surges-as-companies-and-schools-send-people-home"}' ><img src="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/03/17/ap_20077092705919_sq-c6ae9a8a74a41b1cf1b9314232ace7b1daa970b6-s100-c15.jpg" data-original="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/03/17/ap_20077092705919_sq-c6ae9a8a74a41b1cf1b9314232ace7b1daa970b6-s100.jpg" class="img lazyOnLoad"  alt="Internet Traffic Surges As Companies And Schools Send People Home" /></a>         <div class="bucketblock">
                        <h3 class="slug"><a href="https://www.npr.org/series/812054919/the-coronavirus-crisis">The Coronavirus Crisis </a></h3>
            <h3><a href="https://www.npr.org/2020/03/17/817154787/internet-traffic-surges-as-companies-and-schools-send-people-home"  data-metrics='{"category":"Story to Story","action":"Click Internal Link","label":"https:\/\/www.npr.org\/2020\/03\/17\/817154787\/internet-traffic-surges-as-companies-and-schools-send-people-home"}' >Internet Traffic Surges As Companies And Schools Send People Home</a></h3>
         </div>
         
<!-- END CLASS="BUCKETBLOCK" -->
      </div>
      
<!-- END CLASS="BUCKET IMG" -->
   </div>
   
<!-- END ID="RES826164631" CLASS="BUCKETWRAP INTERNALLINK INSETTWOCOLUMN INSET2COL " -->
   <p>Zoombombers have disrupted an <a href="https://www.businessinsider.com/aa-intergroup-meetings-zoom-bombing-trolls-alcoholics-anonymous-2020-3">Alcoholics Anonymous meeting</a> in New York, <a href="https://religionnews.com/2020/03/30/zoombombing-epidemic-comes-for-houses-of-worship/">Sunday school</a> in Texas, <a href="https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2020/03/26/zoombombers-disrupt-online-classes-racist-pornographic-content">online classes</a> at the University of Southern California and a <a href="https://www.mlive.com/news/kalamazoo/2020/04/internet-trolls-spew-profanity-racial-slurs-during-first-virtual-kalamazoo-city-meeting.html">city meeting</a> in Kalamazoo, Mich.</p>   <p>With schools closed and millions of people <a href="https://www.npr.org/2020/03/17/817154787/internet-traffic-surges-as-companies-and-schools-send-people-home">working from home</a>, Zoom has become wildly popular. The company said 200 million people used the app on a daily basis in March, up from just 10 million in December. But that newfound popularity is bringing new scrutiny.</p>   <p>The FBI is warning schools, in particular, to be careful.</p>   <p>"The FBI has received multiple reports of conferences being disrupted by pornographic and/or hate images and threatening language," the bureau's <a href="https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/boston/news/press-releases/fbi-warns-of-teleconferencing-and-online-classroom-hijacking-during-covid-19-pandemic">Boston office</a> said this week.</p>   <div id="res826172701" class="bucketwrap twitter large graphic624" aria-label="Tweet">
            <blockquote class="twitter-tweet"><p lang="en" dir="ltr"><a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/FBI?src=hash&amp;ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">#FBI</a> warns of Teleconferencing and Online Classroom Hijacking during <a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/COVID19?src=hash&amp;ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">#COVID19</a> pandemic. Find out how to report and protect against teleconference hijacking threats here: <a href="https://t.co/jmMxyZZqMv">https://t.co/jmMxyZZqMv</a> <a href="https://t.co/Y3h9bVZG30">pic.twitter.com/Y3h9bVZG30</a></p>&mdash; FBI Boston (@FBIBoston) <a href="https://twitter.com/FBIBoston/status/1244710356385173511?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">March 30, 2020</a></blockquote>
<script async src="https://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>
   </div>
   
<!-- END ID="RES826172701" CLASS="BUCKETWRAP TWITTER LARGE GRAPHIC624" ARIA-LABEL="TWEET" -->
   <p>As concerns have arisen, Zoom has worked to address them. It published a <a href="https://blog.zoom.us/wordpress/2020/03/20/keep-uninvited-guests-out-of-your-zoom-event/">guide</a> last month on how users can protect meetings. It also changed settings for accounts used by schools and universities to make their meetings more private by default.</p>   <p>New York Attorney General Letitia James has sent a <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/technology/new-york-attorney-general-zoom-privacy.html">letter to Zoom</a> asking about its security and privacy protections.</p>   <div id="res826611905" class="bucketwrap internallink insettwocolumn inset2col ">
            <div class="bucket img">
                  <a id="featuredStackSquareImage822245048" href="https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/26/822245048/facebook-steps-up-efforts-to-combat-the-spread-of-coronavirus-misinformation"  data-metrics='{"category":"Story to Story","action":"Click Internal Link","label":"https:\/\/www.npr.org\/sections\/coronavirus-live-updates\/2020\/03\/26\/822245048\/facebook-steps-up-efforts-to-combat-the-spread-of-coronavirus-misinformation"}' ><img src="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/03/26/v2-cropped-e1585160266279_sq-8bd2188e9b959c1966de83aabba88365e7cb1786-s100-c15.png" data-original="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/03/26/v2-cropped-e1585160266279_sq-8bd2188e9b959c1966de83aabba88365e7cb1786-s100.png" class="img lazyOnLoad"  alt="Facebook Steps Up Efforts To Combat The Spread Of Coronavirus Misinformation" /></a>         <div class="bucketblock">
                        <h3 class="slug"><a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/">Coronavirus Live Updates </a></h3>
            <h3><a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/26/822245048/facebook-steps-up-efforts-to-combat-the-spread-of-coronavirus-misinformation"  data-metrics='{"category":"Story to Story","action":"Click Internal Link","label":"https:\/\/www.npr.org\/sections\/coronavirus-live-updates\/2020\/03\/26\/822245048\/facebook-steps-up-efforts-to-combat-the-spread-of-coronavirus-misinformation"}' >Facebook Steps Up Efforts To Combat The Spread Of Coronavirus Misinformation</a></h3>
         </div>
         
<!-- END CLASS="BUCKETBLOCK" -->
      </div>
      
<!-- END CLASS="BUCKET IMG" -->
   </div>
   
<!-- END ID="RES826611905" CLASS="BUCKETWRAP INTERNALLINK INSETTWOCOLUMN INSET2COL " -->
   <p>"Things you just would like to have in a chat and video application — strong encryption, strong privacy controls, strong security — just seem to be completely missing," said Patrick Wardle, a security researcher who previously worked at the National Security Agency.</p>   <p>He and other researchers have turned up flaws in Zoom's software that could let hackers spy through a computer's webcam or microphone. Zoom says it released fixes for these issues on Wednesday.</p>   <div id="res826169371" class="bucketwrap internallink mediapromo primary">
            <h4 class="internallink__slug">Technology</h4>
      <h2 class="internallink__title">An Etiquette Primer For Zoom And Other Videoconferencing Services</h2>
